fields.descriptive_line: Pack of cards (68) for the game of Snap; Lithography and screenprinting, some coloured (the backs screenprinted); In a box with rules for the game, list of contributors etc.; Designed and printed by 34 artists (staff and students) at the Royal College of Art, London, including Leslie Biggs; England; ca.1975.
fields.physical_description: Pack of cards (68) for the game of Snap; Lithography and screenprinting, some coloured (the backs screenprinted); In a box with rules for the game, list of contributors etc pasted inside the lid, and a card, back upwards, pasted on the outside of the lid; Numbered in red on the inside bottom of the box R.C.A. 39/120.
fields.dimensions: Height: 14.9 cm each card, Width: 11.7 cm each card
fields.materials_techniques: lithography and screenprinting, some coloured (the backs screenprinted)
fields.location: Prints & Drawings Study Room, level C, case MB2F, shelf SH66, box 98A2
fields.marks: R.C.A. 39/120 Rules for the game, list of contributors etc pasted inside the lid of the box, and a card, back upwards, pasted on the outside of the lid.

fields.bibliography: Hamilton, Jean. Playing Cards in the Victoria & Albert Museum. Victoria & Albert Museum. Her Majesty's Stationery Office. London, 1988, p.40, ill. The full text of the entry is as follows: '10 BIGGS, Leslie (born 1944), and other artists Pack of cards (68) for the game of Snap, designed and printed by 34 artists (staff and students) at the Royal College of Art, London, c. 1975. In a box with rules for the game, list of contributors etc pasted inside the lid, and a card, back upwards, pasted on the outside of the lid. Numbered in red on the inside bottom of the box R.C.A. 39/120. Lithography and screenprinting, some coloured (the backs screenprinted). Each 14.9 x 11.7 cm; in box 15.7 x 12.6 cm. E.36.1-68-1976 Given by the Printmaking Department of the Royal College of Art' Hamilton, Jean. Playing Cards in the Victoria & Albert Museum. Victoria & Albert Museum. Her Majesty's Stationery Office. London, 1988, p.11. The relevant text of the passage is as follows: 'Twentieth century English packs in the collection include a Snap game designed, lithographed and screenprinted by the staff and students of the Royal College of Art, c1975 (10)'
fields.credit: Given by the Printmaking Department of the Royal College of Art'
fields.production_note: Designed and printed by 34 artists (staff and students) at the Royal College of Art, London.
